      <field name="heading_text">WINTER IN THE SIERRAS</field>
      <field name="fulltext">BY MARY AUSTIN â€”</field>
      <field name="fulltext">Digital image of poem and accompanying illustration</field>
      <field name="fulltext">T HE pines are black on Sierra's slope, And white are the drifted snows; The flowers are gone, the buckthorn bare, And chilly the north wind blows. The pine-boughs creak, And the pine-trees speak A language the north wind knows.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">There's never a track leads in or out Of the cave of the big brown bear; The squirrels have hid in their deepest holes, And fastened the doors with care. The red fox prowls, And the lean wolf howls As he hunts far down from the lair.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">The eagle hangs on the wing all day, On the chance of a single kill; The little gray hawk hunts far and wide Before he can get his fell. The snow-wreaths sift, And the blown snows drift To the canyons deep and still.</field>
